<p><b>Richard Hamilton</b>, <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_Companions_of_Honour" title="Order of the Companions of Honour">CH</a> (born February 24, 1922) is an <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">English</a> <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painter</a> and <a href="/wiki/Collage" title="Collage">collage</a> artist. His 1956 <a href="/wiki/Collage" title="Collage">collage</a> titled <i><a href="/wiki/Just_What_Is_It_that_Makes_Today%27s_Homes_So_Different,_So_Appealing%3F" title="Just What Is It that Makes Today's Homes So Different, So Appealing?">Just What Is It that Makes Today's Homes So Different, So Appealing?</a></i>, produced for the <i><a href="/wiki/This_Is_Tomorrow" title="This Is Tomorrow">This Is Tomorrow</a></i> exhibition of the <a href="/wiki/Independent_Group" title="Independent Group">Independent Group</a> in <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>, is considered by critics and historians to be one of the early works of <a href="/wiki/Pop_Art" title="Pop Art" class="mw-redirect">Pop Art</a>. <sup id="cite_ref-Livingstone1990_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Livingstone1990-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
